-- Oil Options Slip From Three-Month High as Futures Jump 1.2%
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-04-18T19:25:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-18/oil-options-slip-from-three-month-high-as-futures-jump-1-2-.html
Crude options volatility slipped
from a three-month high as the underlying futures jumped 1.2
percent in the first gain in five days.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 25.35 percent at 2:40 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , down from 27.95 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery rose $1.03
to settle at $88 a barrel on the Nymex, the largest gain since
March 26.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
June $75 puts, which sank 14 cents to 24 cents a barrel on
volume of 6,894 contracts at 2:49 p.m. June $70 puts were the
second-most active, dropping 7 cents to 9 cents on volume of
6,509 lots.  Puts accounted for 65 percent of electronic trading volume
today. Bearish bets made up 67 percent of yesterdayâ€™s volume of
231,795 contracts.  June $80 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 10,963 contracts changing hands. They
rose 43 cents to 90 cents a barrel. July $75 puts increased 32
cents to 72 cents a barrel on 10,905 lots.  Open interest was highest for June $80 puts with 37,789
contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 36,100 and June
$85 puts with 33,785.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-
outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
